Piqued by the low contribution of the Nigerian manufacturing sector to the country’s Gross Domestic Product (GDP), Minister of Power, Works and Housing, Babatunde Raji Fashola and its counterparts in Industry Trade and Investment, Dr. Okey Enelamah; Mines, Steel Development, Alhaji Abubakar Bwari and other key industrialists, have urged President Muhammadu Buhari to take a critical look at Nigeria’s real sector, examine how it can play a lead role towards Nigeria achieving a more inclusive industrial development.   The ministers and industrialists, which included the Director-General, Raw Materials Research Development Council (RMRDC), Prof. Zanaib Hamanga Ibrahim; President, Manufacturers Association of Nigeria (MAN), Engr. Mansur Ahmed; Director-General, NOTAP, Alhaji Asumi Ibrahim; National President, Nigerian Association of Chambers of Commerce, Industry, Mines and Agriculture (NACCIMA), Chief Alaba Lawson and Chairman, Flour Mills of Nigeria (FMN) Plc, John Coumantaros, made this disclosure at the opening ceremony of the annual Nigerian manufacturing and equipment expo in Lagos yesterday.  They explained that obstinate challenges in the country’s manufacturing sector, including the widening infrastructure deficit, unfavourable policies, dwindling consumer spending, and other effects had taken toll on manufacturing bottom line, which was already grappling for survival.  They said all was not yet well with the state of the country’s manufacturing sector in terms of increased capacity building, capacity utilisation, local sourcing of raw materials and marketing.